04807nam a22007695i 9780813562773DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142014nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2013042858  a97808135627737 a10.36019/97808135627732doi  a(DE-B1597)526239  a(OCoLC)895258815  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aHV9475.O5bS53 2014 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a365/.6082097662231 aSharp, Susan F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMean Lives, Mean Laws :bOklahoma's Women Prisoners /cSusan F. Sharp. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (210 p.) :b2 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical Issues in Crime and Society00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. Mean Lives: A Theoretical Framework -- t2. Mean Laws: The Rise in Female Imprisonment -- t3. Mean Women or Mean Lives? Adverse Childhood Experiences and Adult Abuse of Women Prisoners -- t4. The Prison Experience -- t5. Going Back Again -- t6. Coming Home and Staying Out -- t7. The Children and Their Caregivers -- t8. Winds of Change -- t9. Lessons Learned and Moving Forward -- tAppendix A. Research Methods -- tAppendix B. Oklahoma Children of Incarcerated Parents -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOklahoma has long held the dubious honor of having the highest female incarceration rate in the country, nearly twice the national average. In this compelling new book, sociologist Susan Sharp sets out to discover just what has gone so wrong in the state of Oklahoma—and what that might tell us about trends in female incarceration nationwide. The culmination of over a decade of original research, Mean Lives, Mean Laws exposes a Kafkaesque criminal justice system, one that has no problem with treating women as collateral damage in the War on Drugs or with stripping female prisoners of their parental rights. Yet it also reveals the individual histories of women who were jailed in Oklahoma, providing intimate portraits of their lives before, during, and after their imprisonment. We witness the impoverished and abusive conditions in which many of these women were raised; we get a vivid portrait of their everyday lives behind bars; and we glimpse the struggles that lead many ex-convicts to fall back into the penal system. Through an innovative methodology that combines statistical rigor with extensive personal interviews, Sharp shows how female incarceration affects not only individuals, but also families and communities. Putting a human face on a growing social problem, Mean Lives, Mean Laws raises important questions about both the state of Oklahoma and the state of the nation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aChildren of prisonerszOklahoma. 0aCorrectionszOklahoma. 0aFemale offendersxRehabilitationzOklahoma. 0aReformatories for womenzOklahoma. 0aWomen prisonerszOklahoma. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aOrtiz, Juanita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOrtiz, Juanita.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066615140uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081356277340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813562773423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813562773.jpg  a978-3-11-066615-1  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE